14
00:00:57,993 --> 00:01:01,616
Then iPhone happened, and the playbook was rewritten.

15
00:01:02,356 --> 00:01:05,839
I was working on the first mobile location-based MMO

16
00:01:05,939 --> 00:01:08,461
Shadows at least, and after that, I've been working on

17
00:01:08,501 --> 00:01:10,343
different mobile gaming startups in

18
00:01:10,363 --> 00:01:12,204
Helsinki since then.

19
00:01:14,403 --> 00:01:18,966
Well, so today's topics.

20
00:01:19,547 --> 00:01:21,648
So we're basically going to talk about how we made the

21
00:01:21,748 --> 00:01:23,970
original source of gameplay for the game.

22
00:01:25,151 --> 00:01:27,913
And to get you started, we're going to first basically

23
00:01:27,953 --> 00:01:29,374
explain what the game is.

24
00:01:30,034 --> 00:01:31,455
So how many of you have actually played it?

25
00:01:33,883 --> 00:01:35,523
Okay, quite a few. Awesome.

26
00:01:36,323 --> 00:01:38,344
But for the rest of you, to give some context,

27
00:01:38,764 --> 00:01:41,825
then we're going to be talking about the prototyping and pre-production research

28
00:01:42,205 --> 00:01:46,145
and things that we did to really figure out what the game was that we wanted to build

29
00:01:46,906 --> 00:01:49,606
and then about some of the designs that we actually landed on.

30
00:01:50,026 --> 00:01:53,227
So Walking Dead Our World, it's a location-based game.

31
00:01:53,507 --> 00:01:57,748
It's a single shard MMO, world scale,

32
00:01:57,808 --> 00:01:59,728
where every single one of the players is in the same...

33
00:02:00,337 --> 00:02:01,198
reality.

34
00:02:01,258 --> 00:02:04,759
Same to same missions, you can persist things on the map so you can actually put that stuff

35
00:02:04,779 --> 00:02:05,939
down, other people will see it.

36
00:02:07,520 --> 00:02:11,641
And you basically play the game by going to these missions that you see around you, kill

37
00:02:11,661 --> 00:02:16,963
the walkers, get some collectibles, and become more powerful to go into even harder missions.

38
00:02:17,821 --> 00:02:25,209
And this being based on the TV series, it features a lot of the characters from the TV series as collectibles.

39
00:02:25,229 --> 00:02:35,740
So you can actually find and play with the actual show cast and get them to be more powerful and help you in the missions as well as collecting weapons that you can use yourself.

40
00:02:36,617 --> 00:02:38,159
And when you go to the missions, it kind of looks like this.

41
00:02:38,179 --> 00:02:40,843
So here I'm with Carl shooting some zombies.

42
00:02:41,324 --> 00:02:44,028
You can use AR if your phone is compatible.

43
00:02:44,048 --> 00:02:48,254
So they actually like do real world human scale AR things, which is really cool.

44
00:02:50,538 --> 00:02:58,220
Last but not least, we do a guild system where each one of the players is pushed into a guild very early on during the game where you can chat.

45
00:02:58,340 --> 00:03:13,684
But they also have these task boards where you start to complete these tasks together collaboratively with the rest of the guild and unlock some of the best rewards and then get progressively harder challenges as a group to complete.

46
00:03:14,474 --> 00:03:20,519
And this actually turned out to be a lot more successful than we thought it would.

47
00:03:20,539 --> 00:03:26,604
Where for me as a game designer, basically I've been reading some of the feedback we've been getting on this particular feature.

48
00:03:27,765 --> 00:03:34,211
And people are telling us crazy stuff like somebody is biking 30 kilometers every freaking day

49
00:03:34,731 --> 00:03:39,416
to complete more missions to actually be able to help the guild advance in the tasks.

50
00:03:40,597 --> 00:03:47,503
And a lot of people actually telling that they never quite felt this deeply about collaborative social gameplay in any of the games that they've played before.

51
00:03:48,264 --> 00:03:56,992
Which I think is a really cool achievement for me as a game designer to actually be able to pull it off in a small mobile game.

52
00:03:58,778 --> 00:04:03,121
So how did we end up on this and creating a Walking Dead game in the first place?

53
00:04:03,181 --> 00:04:08,445
So the previous game we made was called The Walking Dead Domain's Land, which is a tactical

54
00:04:08,826 --> 00:04:13,409
kind of like turn-based shooter. Looks a bit like maybe XCOM but super simplified for mobile.

55
00:04:14,370 --> 00:04:21,275
And we featured similar elements where you were collecting the show cast, you made teams of three,

56
00:04:22,196 --> 00:04:27,140
went into missions and like of different types like solve little puzzles with these guys.

57
00:04:28,009 --> 00:04:31,071
And we were really happy about how this game turned out.

58
00:04:31,491 --> 00:04:34,773
And AMC seemed to really enjoy us as well and like the game.

59
00:04:34,793 --> 00:04:38,596
And simultaneously, the Walking Dead as TV series

60
00:04:39,296 --> 00:04:40,817
is still doing incredibly well.

61
00:04:40,917 --> 00:04:42,639
So back when we were starting the project,

62
00:04:42,679 --> 00:04:44,880
we were looking at the show and figured that like,

63
00:04:45,921 --> 00:04:48,483
the brand has some true longevity.

64
00:04:49,123 --> 00:04:50,824
And AMC was quite happy with us,

65
00:04:50,864 --> 00:04:53,326
so we figured it's kind of like a no-brainer

66
00:04:53,426 --> 00:04:56,068
to make another game with those guys.

67
00:04:57,584 --> 00:05:05,708
And at Next, when we start working on new projects, one of the things we really want to do is figure out gameplay mechanics in the games that make sense from the brand perspective.

68
00:05:06,188 --> 00:05:16,012
So we primarily do games based on IPs, and now that we were creating a new game for The Walking Dead, we wanted to figure out what would be a logical combination for that brand.

69
00:05:17,004 --> 00:05:25,727
And many of the viewers of the show actually like were telling us that they have this core fantasy of like really thinking what they would do if the zombie infestation actually happened.

70
00:05:26,288 --> 00:05:41,933
So we figured that like, let's maybe try to prototype location based gaming and see if that works, because it's a really good brand fit actually, like being able to really put you in the situation where like now you're alone, you need to get better weapons, better teams to be able to survive the zombies.

71
00:05:43,191 --> 00:05:46,512
Now, this being the beginning of the project, we kind of figured,

72
00:05:46,592 --> 00:05:49,633
OK, let's actually look at location-based gaming, what's

73
00:05:49,653 --> 00:05:52,434
been done in the genre before, to understand it better.

74
00:05:53,074 --> 00:05:57,695
But also come up with a really live in the present and plan

75
00:05:57,715 --> 00:05:59,916
for the launch, where you need to come up

76
00:05:59,956 --> 00:06:01,516
with a feature set that's actually

77
00:06:01,536 --> 00:06:03,977
doable in high quality during the production,

78
00:06:04,797 --> 00:06:06,878
which has to be also really competitive when

79
00:06:06,898 --> 00:06:07,558
the game goes out.

80
00:06:07,964 --> 00:06:12,068
So I think one of the big problems is when you have a production schedule of a couple of years,

81
00:06:12,489 --> 00:06:17,895
you need to figure out a set of features and gameplay that's going to be competitive and

82
00:06:17,935 --> 00:06:21,579
compelling to the players when you actually ship the game when the market's already changed to

83
00:06:21,619 --> 00:06:27,886
something different. So what can we learn from the past? Shadow Cities is like where you will

84
00:06:27,906 --> 00:06:29,127
actually look into multiple games.

85
00:06:30,157 --> 00:06:36,021
Including Shadow Cities, one of the really early ones that Marcos had made back in the day.

86
00:06:36,161 --> 00:06:42,285
And the gameplay basically was that you could build resource production buildings on the map,

87
00:06:43,145 --> 00:06:47,908
become more powerful, build teleports that allowed people to cooperate and travel the world.

88
00:06:48,389 --> 00:06:52,851
Super interesting. But also featured really brutal PvP, where when you logged in,

89
00:06:52,931 --> 00:06:56,734
you could see your surroundings, but all the other players immediately as well.

90
00:06:57,514 --> 00:07:00,736
And if they weren't powerful, you just got ganked immediately.

91
00:07:01,797 --> 00:07:04,898
And that was kind of really cool if you were the most powerful kid on the block.

92
00:07:05,358 --> 00:07:05,999
But many weren't.

93
00:07:06,659 --> 00:07:11,622
So the location where you logged in and what time of the day really mattered.

94
00:07:11,682 --> 00:07:16,004
Because you started to learn these patterns of where the other powerful players were.

95
00:07:16,044 --> 00:07:19,786
That's the areas to actually avoid due to some of the other players being there.

96
00:07:21,845 --> 00:07:28,710
Pokémon Go had just come out, so it was in the early stages of a lot of people trying to play the game.

97
00:07:29,771 --> 00:07:35,895
And this used a fundamentally different design from what Shadow Cities had done back in the day.

98
00:07:36,316 --> 00:07:42,520
In Pokémon, one of the things compared to Shadow Cities is that Shadow Cities gives you perfect information as a player immediately.

99
00:07:42,540 --> 00:07:45,442
So everything on the map was immediately interactable and you could see it.

100
00:07:46,095 --> 00:07:48,716
In Pokemon, they actually hide the vast majority of the content,

101
00:07:48,996 --> 00:07:52,298
and they want to incentivize you to move to be able to play the game,

102
00:07:52,338 --> 00:07:54,979
so you find the things on the world,

103
00:07:55,579 --> 00:07:57,860
and you could really not play without moving at all.

104
00:07:58,501 --> 00:08:00,081
Some of the content was obviously visible,

105
00:08:00,121 --> 00:08:03,063
so if you wanted to get more Pokeballs,

106
00:08:03,103 --> 00:08:07,665
you'd need to go to the PokeStops you did see somewhere around in your neighborhood.

107
00:08:07,965 --> 00:08:09,406
And in order to access a gym,

108
00:08:09,426 --> 00:08:12,427
it's very likely that you again needed to move,

109
00:08:12,507 --> 00:08:13,888
because they've been so sparsely...

110
00:08:15,154 --> 00:08:18,436
placed in the world that it was quite unlikely there was anything next to you.

111
00:08:19,918 --> 00:08:23,801
And with Pokémon, one of the other things I got asked a lot in the early stages of the project,

112
00:08:23,821 --> 00:08:29,686
like how do we replicate this level of success? Or I think the primary reason why Pokémon is so

113
00:08:29,746 --> 00:08:35,011
successful is, again, simply the fact that the activities the players do in the game is an

114
00:08:35,831 --> 00:08:40,275
excellent, like, real brand fit that people were expecting to make in the game.

115
00:08:40,844 --> 00:08:44,926
So if you see the animated series ever, you're going to expect it.

116
00:08:44,966 --> 00:08:48,468
Yeah, I'm going to walk around the world and throw balls at the Pokemon and collect them.

117
00:08:48,729 --> 00:08:50,430
And this is exactly what you do in the game.

118
00:08:50,470 --> 00:08:54,052
So the mental model that people had in their heads before they started playing

119
00:08:54,112 --> 00:08:58,315
perfectly matched the gameplay that they actually got when they started playing the game.

120
00:09:02,713 --> 00:09:05,974
So the hard thing when you start making a location-based

121
00:09:06,014 --> 00:09:08,795
game is that there are not really that many

122
00:09:09,315 --> 00:09:10,295
location-based games.

123
00:09:10,475 --> 00:09:12,415
And especially, there are not that many successful

124
00:09:12,455 --> 00:09:13,356
location-based games.

125
00:09:14,036 --> 00:09:17,536
So when we started, we knew that we would be, again, into

126
00:09:17,636 --> 00:09:20,837
a very exciting and challenging endeavor where we

127
00:09:21,137 --> 00:09:23,438
would need to figure out a lot of basic

128
00:09:23,478 --> 00:09:24,438
stuff from the get-go.

129
00:09:25,858 --> 00:09:28,739
The thing is that usually when you see people playing mobile

130
00:09:28,779 --> 00:09:31,079
games, the play pattern is something like this.

131
00:09:32,249 --> 00:09:35,690
You're somewhere, and then you play there for two seconds,

132
00:09:35,911 --> 00:09:36,991
and then you go somewhere else.

133
00:09:38,311 --> 00:09:40,272
Most mobile games are not really mobile.

134
00:09:40,692 --> 00:09:43,033
Location-based games are actually mobile.

135
00:09:43,834 --> 00:09:46,975
So we had to face all these kind of different play

136
00:09:47,035 --> 00:09:48,495
patterns that players might have.

137
00:09:48,936 --> 00:09:51,797
We had to figure out from the design angle, again, based on

138
00:09:51,817 --> 00:09:54,018
Shadow Cities, based on Pokemon Go, based on other

139
00:09:54,058 --> 00:09:57,659
games, how would players maybe possibly use this game?

140
00:09:59,148 --> 00:09:59,888
This would be me.

141
00:10:00,168 --> 00:10:01,849
Most of the time, I'm a commuter player.

142
00:10:02,089 --> 00:10:05,110
So if I'm at work, if I'm at home, if I'm at a games

143
00:10:05,170 --> 00:10:08,411
conference, if I'm in the bus, that's when I play.

144
00:10:09,111 --> 00:10:10,891
This is one of our key use cases.

145
00:10:11,712 --> 00:10:14,452
But we have to also figure, how is this game going to work

146
00:10:14,492 --> 00:10:17,313
for people who walk their dogs for one hour every day?

147
00:10:17,853 --> 00:10:19,914
And how are we going to keep it balanced for them?

148
00:10:21,578 --> 00:10:23,560
Some people like to jog a lot.

149
00:10:23,940 --> 00:10:26,783
They like to play real-world games while they're jogging.

150
00:10:27,684 --> 00:10:29,727
We don't necessarily approve, but this is something they

151
00:10:29,747 --> 00:10:31,528
will anyway do, so we have to figure out how

152
00:10:31,568 --> 00:10:32,009
to deal with it.

153
00:10:33,647 --> 00:10:36,507
Something we learned once we actually had launched the game,

154
00:10:36,887 --> 00:10:38,288
we had a lot of tram riders.

155
00:10:38,768 --> 00:10:41,169
Trams move a little bit slower than buses, so they are

156
00:10:41,249 --> 00:10:44,689
perfect for playing The Walking Dead Our World.

157
00:10:46,010 --> 00:10:48,610
You're sitting in the tram, you're grinding a mission, and

158
00:10:48,650 --> 00:10:50,551
the reason why you're sitting in the tram is that you're

159
00:10:51,131 --> 00:10:53,132
trying to grind as efficiently as you can.

160
00:10:53,492 --> 00:10:56,312
We had half of our team sitting in the tram one week

161
00:10:56,352 --> 00:10:58,113
when we were in the soft launch trying to

162
00:10:58,173 --> 00:10:59,013
optimize on a mission.

163
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:02,014
The key point you have to decide is.

164
00:11:02,988 --> 00:11:09,164
Do you want the players to move in order to play, or do you want them to play while they're already on the move?

165
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:13,335
This is how Helsinki looks like.

166
00:11:13,695 --> 00:11:14,936
Next Games is based on Helsinki.

167
00:11:14,996 --> 00:11:16,918
And you can see the little dots on the map.

168
00:11:16,938 --> 00:11:20,261
They are the Google POIs where we spawn all our content.

169
00:11:21,262 --> 00:11:23,103
And when you're looking at this kind of map and when

170
00:11:23,123 --> 00:11:26,506
you're working in this kind of a city, you get all these

171
00:11:26,906 --> 00:11:30,029
exciting ideas about how this kind of a game could work.

172
00:11:30,850 --> 00:11:33,532
Maybe you go to a gas station to get some gas, and then you

173
00:11:33,572 --> 00:11:36,775
go to, I don't know, to the riverfront to get some fish,

174
00:11:36,835 --> 00:11:37,755
and then you craft something.

175
00:11:39,095 --> 00:11:41,676
And that's, of course, a very good way of doing a game if

176
00:11:41,716 --> 00:11:43,836
you make a full collector game, like, for

177
00:11:43,876 --> 00:11:44,576
instance, Pokemon.

178
00:11:45,237 --> 00:11:48,498
But we knew that the brand of The Walking Dead is not about

179
00:11:48,778 --> 00:11:49,658
assembling collections.

180
00:11:49,718 --> 00:11:50,538
It's about something else.

181
00:11:50,578 --> 00:11:52,559
It's about survival and fighting and that kind of

182
00:11:52,579 --> 00:11:54,900
stuff. So we couldn't really do that.

183
00:11:55,720 --> 00:11:59,081
And the reality is that much of the map looks like this.

184
00:11:59,601 --> 00:12:01,582
This is Kansas in our world.

185
00:12:01,922 --> 00:12:04,803
You can, again, see the POIs on the few roads

186
00:12:04,823 --> 00:12:05,443
that you have there.

187
00:12:07,688 --> 00:12:11,950
We couldn't really afford to have the fantasy of going to the gas station to get some gas,

188
00:12:11,990 --> 00:12:18,192
because let's face it, we are in the mobile free-to-play market, and mobile free-to-play

189
00:12:18,232 --> 00:12:19,113
market is about...

190
00:12:20,329 --> 00:12:23,211
about allowing players to generate value

191
00:12:23,251 --> 00:12:24,652
through going through core loop,

192
00:12:25,193 --> 00:12:26,974
iterating over the core loop again and again.

193
00:12:27,494 --> 00:12:28,475
And if you're in this business,

194
00:12:28,495 --> 00:12:29,916
you have to be able to get the player

195
00:12:30,056 --> 00:12:31,717
into the core loop and out of the core loop

196
00:12:31,737 --> 00:12:32,898
and again into the core loop

197
00:12:33,579 --> 00:12:35,420
multiple times during their first session,

198
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:36,601
no matter where they start.

199
00:12:37,461 --> 00:12:39,523
And since we were not doing a full collector,

200
00:12:40,003 --> 00:12:41,925
we had to make sure that our game

201
00:12:41,945 --> 00:12:43,586
was always playable everywhere

202
00:12:43,946 --> 00:12:46,608
and it would be nice and exciting experience

203
00:12:46,828 --> 00:12:47,649
no matter where you were.

204
00:12:48,538 --> 00:12:53,319
Of course, you can add that kind of frills later, but fundamentally we had to be a core loop game.

205
00:12:55,059 --> 00:12:56,920
So, we went back to the basic.

206
00:12:58,020 --> 00:13:03,742
Let's forget about the location for a moment and let's focus on how to make a really great mobile game.

207
00:13:05,702 --> 00:13:11,243
Like many other designers, we got highly inspired by the self-determination theory of motivation.

208
00:13:12,258 --> 00:13:17,101
If you provide players with competence, if you provide players with autonomy, and if

209
00:13:17,141 --> 00:13:21,845
you provide players with relatedness, then they will be highly motivated to play your

210
00:13:21,885 --> 00:13:22,185
game.

211
00:13:22,966 --> 00:13:26,208
This is one very good recipe for a very good game.

212
00:13:28,049 --> 00:13:33,113
Especially we identified the relatedness as a key USP that we could reach in the game.

213
00:13:34,280 --> 00:13:38,743
Other location-based games are also social, but we wanted to focus on guild play.

214
00:13:38,784 --> 00:13:44,188
We wanted to focus on the inclined social, because that is very much what the series

215
00:13:44,248 --> 00:13:45,529
is also about.

216
00:13:46,230 --> 00:13:49,652
It's about pulling together, not apart, as Rick Grimes would say.

217
00:13:51,454 --> 00:13:57,399
So based on this round work, we started shaping up these core design pillars.

218
00:13:58,922 --> 00:13:59,722
Play everywhere.

219
00:14:00,383 --> 00:14:03,424
Wherever you log in for the first time, wherever you log

220
00:14:03,444 --> 00:14:09,668
in for the first time on every day, you will get a full and

221
00:14:09,768 --> 00:14:11,650
interesting complete session in there.

222
00:14:12,830 --> 00:14:15,192
It's always worth opening the game in the new location.

223
00:14:15,492 --> 00:14:17,753
There needs to be enough discovery that I want to see

224
00:14:17,793 --> 00:14:18,554
what's surrounding me.

225
00:14:19,712 --> 00:14:21,192
We wanted to support couch play.

226
00:14:21,332 --> 00:14:23,392
We wanted to make a little bit more traditional game.

227
00:14:23,932 --> 00:14:26,473
So we wanted to make sure that people who would be mostly

228
00:14:26,513 --> 00:14:29,113
playing at home and at work would have a nice experience

229
00:14:29,413 --> 00:14:29,873
nevertheless.

230
00:14:31,374 --> 00:14:34,754
In our philosophy, getting a better location, moving

