00:30:16,687 --> 00:30:19,148
that we wanted to make sure that at least something

449
00:30:19,188 --> 00:30:20,668
would be tried and true,

450
00:30:20,748 --> 00:30:22,408
and we wouldn't need to figure it all out.

451
00:30:22,829 --> 00:30:25,609
So basically, you collect weapons, you collect heroes,

452
00:30:25,649 --> 00:30:28,030
and you collect some other items from the series,

453
00:30:28,410 --> 00:30:30,350
and then you level them up,

454
00:30:30,911 --> 00:30:32,611
just as if you were playing Clash Royale.

455
00:30:35,092 --> 00:30:37,232
We want the players to unite with other players.

456
00:30:37,592 --> 00:30:39,073
So in the end of the tutorial,

457
00:30:39,713 --> 00:30:42,093
you will be offered one guild to join.

458
00:30:43,199 --> 00:30:46,600
And the choice is basically, join this guild or search more.

459
00:30:47,240 --> 00:30:51,202
In The Walking Dead No Man's Land, we have learned already at Next Games

460
00:30:51,622 --> 00:30:55,103
that this is the best way we can sort of encourage you to join a guild.

461
00:30:55,363 --> 00:31:00,245
Give you one recommendation, zero decision making anxiety, and join or don't.

462
00:31:00,865 --> 00:31:03,626
We actually intend to be even more aggressive about it in future.

463
00:31:03,906 --> 00:31:06,187
We're actually thinking about forcing players into guild.

464
00:31:06,907 --> 00:31:07,547
Consequently...

465
00:31:09,267 --> 00:31:11,188
90% of our daily active users are in guilds.

466
00:31:11,608 --> 00:31:14,769
And we've learned that the business value in retention

467
00:31:14,809 --> 00:31:18,650
monetization in all respects, that the guilded players are so

468
00:31:18,690 --> 00:31:22,551
much more valuable for us than the other players, that we

469
00:31:22,591 --> 00:31:25,772
don't really lose anything if players who don't want to join

470
00:31:25,792 --> 00:31:27,273
a guild leave our game.

471
00:31:30,514 --> 00:31:33,635
Scavenging is also a big part of The Walking Dead.

472
00:31:34,035 --> 00:31:36,336
And we wanted it to be a big part of our core loop as well.

473
00:31:37,196 --> 00:31:37,336
So.

474
00:31:38,921 --> 00:31:43,450
Every time you log in, you can see some resource crates around you where you can collect things

475
00:31:43,530 --> 00:31:46,597
like energy, you can collect grenades, and first aid kits.

476
00:31:47,817 --> 00:31:52,581
Some free-to-play games decided to make these kind of resources extremely scarce.

477
00:31:52,941 --> 00:31:57,445
They want you to have that one, I don't know, lollipop hammer that you will treasure looking

478
00:31:57,485 --> 00:31:58,566
for the impossible mission.

479
00:31:59,347 --> 00:32:01,869
We wanted to do this in a completely opposite fashion.

480
00:32:02,429 --> 00:32:05,772
In our game, you get consumables all the time.

481
00:32:06,353 --> 00:32:10,997
However, the caps are very low, so you need to also spend them or you end up wasting them.

482
00:32:11,897 --> 00:32:18,039
This creates a loop where you're actually constantly spending consumables, constantly getting consumables,

483
00:32:18,299 --> 00:32:21,360
and sometimes you actually do run out, and that's the monetization point.

484
00:32:21,860 --> 00:32:25,881
But if you want to just, like, if you just walk 100 meters, you will get some more.

485
00:32:26,121 --> 00:32:32,042
So even though it's a pinch, it's not that kind of pinch as we usually think of it in free-to-play games.

486
00:32:34,083 --> 00:32:35,263
So let's look at our core loop.

487
00:32:36,223 --> 00:32:40,765
You log in somewhere. You look around. You will scavenge.

488
00:32:42,314 --> 00:32:42,994
The consumables.

489
00:32:43,895 --> 00:32:45,816
You will take the consumables and spend them

490
00:32:45,836 --> 00:32:46,877
in different kinds of fights.

491
00:32:47,538 --> 00:32:50,280
You will gain cards and coins and survivors.

492
00:32:51,821 --> 00:32:54,163
You take the survivors into safe houses

493
00:32:54,464 --> 00:32:55,725
to get even more cards.

494
00:32:57,026 --> 00:32:59,508
And then you use the cards and coins to upgrade your things.

495
00:33:00,889 --> 00:33:03,011
Rinse and repeat as many times as you like.

496
00:33:06,873 --> 00:33:10,574
So we were not entirely satisfied with this core loop at this point.

497
00:33:10,834 --> 00:33:11,934
It felt a little bit dull.

498
00:33:12,875 --> 00:33:16,076
The players kept requesting all kinds of discovery.

499
00:33:16,116 --> 00:33:18,756
They wanted to really go to that gas station and get some gas.

500
00:33:19,397 --> 00:33:22,258
And we were like, we're a little bit short of resources

501
00:33:22,318 --> 00:33:26,299
and we don't want to do that big an investment in that kind of gameplay.

502
00:33:26,699 --> 00:33:29,060
So we introduced rare and epic missions,

503
00:33:29,480 --> 00:33:31,620
where you would get guaranteed rare and epic cards.

504
00:33:31,740 --> 00:33:33,321
And suddenly players were seeing

505
00:33:34,242 --> 00:33:37,868
a purple glow in the horizon and they would be walking there to see what's in there.

506
00:33:38,169 --> 00:33:40,453
They would be talking in the guild channels like

507
00:33:40,874 --> 00:33:44,440
there's a thing in the market street, if you're near market street you should go there and get it.

508
00:33:46,148 --> 00:33:50,411
We were also introducing both dynamic and static difficulty missions.

509
00:33:51,012 --> 00:33:54,975
We wanted to make sure that there would be always nice content for you to play,

510
00:33:55,055 --> 00:33:58,477
so we had to resort to dynamic difficulty most of the time.

511
00:33:59,177 --> 00:34:02,500
However, if you design a game that only has dynamic difficulty,

512
00:34:02,780 --> 00:34:05,782
you end up in a situation where progress doesn't feel like progress

513
00:34:05,822 --> 00:34:07,623
because the difficulty always increases.

514
00:34:08,204 --> 00:34:14,189
So many of the rare and epic missions we spawn are on the static difficulty, so they communicate to the player like,

515
00:34:14,750 --> 00:34:17,453
if you were a tougher guy, you could also be playing this mission.

516
00:34:19,534 --> 00:34:24,960
So, the core loop is now a little bit more complicated.

517
00:34:25,780 --> 00:34:29,244
There's different rarities of missions, there are different rarities of raids,

518
00:34:29,744 --> 00:34:32,347
and there are a lot more options what you can do while you...

519
00:34:33,121 --> 00:34:38,163
move around. Of course, these are very contextual opportunities, so if you happen to be in a nice location,

520
00:34:38,444 --> 00:34:42,385
then you will have nice opportunities, and if you're not in a nice location, then you have to figure out

521
00:34:42,425 --> 00:34:47,248
whether you conserve your energy and your grenades, or whether you will use them on the bad opportunities

522
00:34:47,308 --> 00:34:48,068
right here, right now.

523
00:34:51,750 --> 00:34:55,171
Sulca mentioned the safe havens. Nowadays, they're called safe houses.

524
00:34:56,052 --> 00:34:58,273
Players can build buildings in our world.

525
00:35:00,239 --> 00:35:03,221
After you've built a building, you can leave survivors there.

526
00:35:03,741 --> 00:35:07,184
You get rewards, and you also improve your rating

527
00:35:07,284 --> 00:35:08,645
in the safe house leaderboard.

528
00:35:09,965 --> 00:35:11,847
If you leave enough rescuees there,

529
00:35:12,187 --> 00:35:14,068
then the safe house will be upgraded.

530
00:35:14,508 --> 00:35:16,790
If you don't upgrade your safe house in a while,

531
00:35:17,070 --> 00:35:19,272
then it will be destroyed by raiders.

532
00:35:21,333 --> 00:35:23,674
We also have different kinds of safe houses

533
00:35:23,714 --> 00:35:25,836
that give you different kinds of cards as rewards.

534
00:35:27,084 --> 00:35:30,387
So suddenly we are facing a surprisingly complex decision space.

535
00:35:30,867 --> 00:35:35,090
You have to figure out whether I want guns or heroes this time, whether it's important

536
00:35:35,150 --> 00:35:39,994
for me to upgrade this safe house, whether it's important for me to beat the other guys

537
00:35:40,054 --> 00:35:44,378
on the leaderboard to become the leader of the safe house and get improved rewards, or

538
00:35:44,418 --> 00:35:48,221
whether it's important for me to save a safe house from destruction.

539
00:35:49,471 --> 00:35:52,374
The leaderboards also have a really nice quality of showing

540
00:35:52,414 --> 00:35:54,596
that other people are also playing around you.

541
00:35:54,957 --> 00:35:58,060
And they create this kind of neighborhood-friendly co-op

542
00:35:58,440 --> 00:36:01,343
competitions where someone is a leader in this house and

543
00:36:01,383 --> 00:36:03,185
someone else is a leader in that house.

544
00:36:03,245 --> 00:36:05,547
And if you try to be too greedy about too many safe

545
00:36:05,587 --> 00:36:08,190
houses, then you actually can't be a leader in any of them.

546
00:36:10,312 --> 00:36:11,493
This is kind of like.

547
00:36:12,663 --> 00:36:15,885
We wanted to make the location a social opportunity for you.

548
00:36:16,166 --> 00:36:19,167
And this kind of simple, kind of complex game

549
00:36:19,187 --> 00:36:21,129
allows for that.

550
00:36:25,171 --> 00:36:27,332
Sulka mentioned that we are a single shard game.

551
00:36:27,613 --> 00:36:28,553
So we are.

552
00:36:29,885 --> 00:36:33,889
Everything in the world is mostly similar to all the players.

553
00:36:34,349 --> 00:36:38,393
So when I can see something cool, I will tell you that it's on the market street and go there.

554
00:36:39,694 --> 00:36:45,439
However, we wanted to also introduce a feature to facilitate that, and that's why we created a feature called Flare.

555
00:36:46,040 --> 00:36:53,126
Flare is a consumable that I can deploy here, and if I deploy a Flare here, all my friends in my guild can teleport here for free.

556
00:36:55,265 --> 00:37:02,071
This helps us a lot in creating kind of a social dynamic where it's somewhat patronage.

557
00:37:02,771 --> 00:37:07,816
It is couch play because I can invite you here while you're, I don't know, ill at home or whatever.

558
00:37:08,557 --> 00:37:14,842
It allows virtual tourism. I have been sharing Moscone Center several times this week because I want to tell everyone that I'm here.

559
00:37:15,683 --> 00:37:21,168
And when we get to the deeper social tasks, the flair allows for added coordination.

560
00:37:23,842 --> 00:37:28,767
So the core loop, let's add some exploration.

561
00:37:30,268 --> 00:37:31,949
So you have different kinds of safe houses.

562
00:37:32,610 --> 00:37:34,352
Now it's starting to become a little bit of a resource

563
00:37:34,392 --> 00:37:35,132
management game.

564
00:37:35,453 --> 00:37:38,195
You have this one survivor, and you have five safe houses

565
00:37:38,295 --> 00:37:40,677
around you, and then you're trying to figure what to do

566
00:37:40,717 --> 00:37:41,178
with this guy.

567
00:37:42,428 --> 00:37:45,593
And the way we built this thing is that it's mostly

568
00:37:46,194 --> 00:37:49,078
cooperative, so everyone is benefiting from this friendly

569
00:37:49,118 --> 00:37:49,639
competition.

570
00:37:50,059 --> 00:37:53,524
But the guys who are playing most actively and making

571
00:37:53,585 --> 00:37:55,628
smartest choices are benefiting even more.

572
00:37:56,985 --> 00:37:58,746
It's also not a very serious game.

573
00:37:59,007 --> 00:38:02,289
The benefits that you get from leaving your survivors

574
00:38:02,390 --> 00:38:04,511
into better safe houses are actually quite small,

575
00:38:04,992 --> 00:38:05,692
but they are nice.

576
00:38:06,313 --> 00:38:08,975
So we wanted to make sure that you can't make mistakes,

577
00:38:09,636 --> 00:38:12,118
but if you're smart, you can be a little bit better

578
00:38:12,158 --> 00:38:12,498
in the game.

579
00:38:14,558 --> 00:38:18,260
Also, we wanted to give an alternative to the walking and

580
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:20,821
discovering, which is the teleportation.

581
00:38:21,181 --> 00:38:24,063
So now you can ask your guildmates to flare you

582
00:38:24,103 --> 00:38:26,804
somewhere, or you can share something that you find and

583
00:38:26,864 --> 00:38:27,725
flare others to there.

584
00:38:28,185 --> 00:38:31,187
You can share the location opportunities to other players.

585
00:38:33,548 --> 00:38:35,789
It looks nicer now, the core loop, but not nice

586
00:38:35,909 --> 00:38:36,610
enough just yet.

587
00:38:39,439 --> 00:38:42,042
Remember this, Sulke showed this and said that nothing felt

588
00:38:42,082 --> 00:38:44,844
as good as seeing the bars progress after a battle, and

589
00:38:44,864 --> 00:38:46,105
this is very much true.

590
00:38:48,567 --> 00:38:52,251
This was a very good prototype for us, and based on this

591
00:38:52,671 --> 00:38:55,954
simple progress bar system, we wanted to develop something a

592
00:38:55,994 --> 00:38:59,197
little bit more sophisticated and, let's be honest, a little

593
00:38:59,217 --> 00:39:00,058
bit more complicated.

594
00:39:01,113 --> 00:39:02,595
So this is a guild board.

595
00:39:03,356 --> 00:39:07,000
It consists of about 25 missions that you complete.

596
00:39:07,761 --> 00:39:09,763
There are also three chests on the board.

597
00:39:10,023 --> 00:39:13,868
And if you complete a row and a column, then you can collect

598
00:39:13,968 --> 00:39:16,771
the chest in the intersection of that row and column.

599
00:39:17,833 --> 00:39:19,415
But the thing is this.

600
00:39:20,326 --> 00:39:25,291
Everyone in your guild is collaboratively completing these quests, and all the rewards are social.

601
00:39:25,672 --> 00:39:32,158
There is no way for you as an individual to benefit any more than everyone in your guild benefits.

602
00:39:32,499 --> 00:39:34,821
When you unlock the chest, everyone unlocks the chest.

603
00:39:35,771 --> 00:39:46,137
The only thing that you can gain in the guild board for yourself is that if you're a top contributor to a task, you get your face on the wall, like the four yellow portraits in the top row.

604
00:39:47,017 --> 00:39:50,479
This has turned out to be a surprisingly strong motivator for players.

605
00:39:50,859 --> 00:39:55,501
Some people want to, I want my face on the wall so that I can prove that I play a lot.

606
00:39:55,782 --> 00:39:59,143
I want my face on the wall so that I won't be kicked away from the guild.

607
00:39:59,504 --> 00:40:03,746
I want my face on the wall because I already have seven and I want more faces on the wall than Sulko has.

608
00:40:06,801 --> 00:40:08,282
This is how the tasks look like.

609
00:40:08,682 --> 00:40:09,723
Win 40 battles.

610
00:40:10,203 --> 00:40:11,384
This is an easy task.

611
00:40:14,006 --> 00:40:16,527
This is actually so easy task that when you start playing

612
00:40:16,567 --> 00:40:18,629
the game and you're in the guild, you start kind of

613
00:40:18,709 --> 00:40:20,270
accidentally completing the quests.

614
00:40:20,330 --> 00:40:23,412
And this is what hooks you into this somewhat complicated

615
00:40:23,452 --> 00:40:24,232
guild board system.

616
00:40:25,738 --> 00:40:29,483
Actually there's a funny story about this screen on the right hand side.

617
00:40:29,864 --> 00:40:33,349
A programmer was implementing this feature and they came to me and they complained like

618
00:40:34,310 --> 00:40:38,416
I just played this mission and I completed seven tasks or incremented seven tasks.

619
00:40:40,038 --> 00:40:44,520
So isn't it a little bit weird to complete seven tasks at one

620
00:40:44,560 --> 00:40:44,741
go?

621
00:40:45,301 --> 00:40:47,662
And I was like, if you choose the optimal hero

622
00:40:47,782 --> 00:40:49,683
and the optimal gun and the optimal mission,

623
00:40:49,763 --> 00:40:51,543
and then you go there with optimal, I don't know,

624
00:40:51,583 --> 00:40:53,344
grenades or something, and you manage

625
00:40:53,384 --> 00:40:55,145
to progress seven missions at the same time,

626
00:40:55,245 --> 00:40:56,045
isn't that cool?

627
00:40:56,786 --> 00:40:59,227
So actually, we ended up designing the easier guild

628
00:40:59,267 --> 00:41:02,428
boards in a way where this is very likely and constantly

629
00:41:02,448 --> 00:41:02,728
happens.

630
00:41:04,125 --> 00:41:06,707
On the later guild boards, on the harder tasks,

631
00:41:07,407 --> 00:41:08,668
you will get these kind of missions.

632
00:41:09,289 --> 00:41:13,251
Lone Wolf, one group member must win 80 level 20 battles

633
00:41:13,531 --> 00:41:14,812
with a reclaimer shotgun.

634
00:41:15,553 --> 00:41:18,034
So suddenly you need to parse together

635
00:41:18,134 --> 00:41:19,355
quite a bit of information

636
00:41:19,395 --> 00:41:21,016
and you need to start sharing tasks.

637
00:41:21,096 --> 00:41:22,517
Who's gonna do the reclaimer task

638
00:41:22,557 --> 00:41:24,118
because someone else is doing something else?

639
00:41:26,330 --> 00:41:30,192
This 25 square board is, in a sense,

640
00:41:30,232 --> 00:41:31,553
it's a simple representation.

641
00:41:31,693 --> 00:41:32,994
In a sense, it's complicated.

642
00:41:33,454 --> 00:41:36,196
But the interesting thing is that it has surprising depth

643
00:41:36,236 --> 00:41:38,377
when you're trying to track the progress of everyone

644
00:41:38,717 --> 00:41:40,658
in your guild and trying to figure out what they are

645
00:41:40,999 --> 00:41:43,580
actually doing and what is your best way of contributing

646
00:41:43,860 --> 00:41:44,861
to the common task.

647
00:41:46,403 --> 00:41:50,005
It's also a great collectible motivator, because if no one

648
00:41:50,045 --> 00:41:52,526
has the reclaimer shotgun, no one's able to

649
00:41:52,586 --> 00:41:53,367
complete that quest.

650
00:41:53,807 --> 00:41:57,369
So this is a way we can shuffle players' collections

651
00:41:57,469 --> 00:41:58,930
around and make sure that even the

652
00:41:58,950 --> 00:42:00,150
weakest weapons are used.

653
00:42:03,452 --> 00:42:06,673
We organized these guild boards into 20 different tiers.

654
00:42:08,594 --> 00:42:11,456
On every tier you have three identical boards.

655
00:42:12,377 --> 00:42:16,659
So the boards are identical except for the target counts of the missions.

656
00:42:16,940 --> 00:42:22,663
So on the first board of the first tier you might need to complete 10 battles, then 20

657
00:42:22,723 --> 00:42:22,943
and then 40.

658
00:42:23,984 --> 00:42:27,807
And we designed this in this way in part because we want the

659
00:42:27,847 --> 00:42:29,468
first board to be a practice board.

660
00:42:29,788 --> 00:42:32,510
Usually the first board takes a good guild about one day.

661
00:42:32,530 --> 00:42:36,693
And that is the one day during which you learn to allocate

662
00:42:36,713 --> 00:42:39,115
your resources and coordinate your efforts so that when you

663
00:42:39,475 --> 00:42:41,456
are tackling the real challenge of the third board,

664
00:42:41,736 --> 00:42:44,438
you will be educated and understanding the

665
00:42:44,718 --> 00:42:45,419
task you have to do.

666
00:42:47,499 --> 00:42:49,381
You have one week to complete every tier.

667
00:42:50,022 --> 00:42:51,964
So this is a time pressured challenge.

668
00:42:52,225 --> 00:42:54,748
And this works really nicely for us in a weekly cycle.

669
00:42:55,228 --> 00:42:57,892
Every Thursday when the boards open,

670
00:42:58,212 --> 00:42:59,974
we can see a peak in the player activity

671
00:42:59,994 --> 00:43:01,576
when everyone is enjoying the fact

672
00:43:01,616 --> 00:43:03,559
that they can progress seven missions at one time

673
00:43:03,899 --> 00:43:05,922
and when they are charging through the easy board.

674
00:43:07,144 --> 00:43:10,906
However, if you don't complete the tier in the week,

675
00:43:11,146 --> 00:43:13,667
then you will be starting that tier over the next week.

676
00:43:13,927 --> 00:43:18,088
So it's also a challenge that becomes harder and harder

677
00:43:18,168 --> 00:43:18,549
every week.

678
00:43:19,929 --> 00:43:22,110
And finally, we have eight weeks in every season.

679
00:43:22,530 --> 00:43:24,091
And we have a leaderboard where we track

680
00:43:24,111 --> 00:43:25,131
the best guilds in the world.

681
00:43:25,831 --> 00:43:27,532
And after the eight-week season, you

682
00:43:27,572 --> 00:43:29,293
will get a massive reward and start over.

683
00:43:32,763 --> 00:43:37,364
We spent a lot of time iterating these guild boards, trying to figure out how we can make

684
00:43:37,424 --> 00:43:37,924
them work.

685
00:43:38,905 --> 00:43:44,666
One important thing we did was that we specifically decided that none of the tasks require you

686
00:43:44,686 --> 00:43:45,806
to be co-located.

687
00:43:46,186 --> 00:43:51,807
So basically, you can play with friends from anywhere in the world and succeed in the guild

688
00:43:51,867 --> 00:43:52,107
boards.

689
00:43:52,447 --> 00:43:57,108
It was far too complicated for us to even plan about the missions that would require

690
00:43:57,188 --> 00:44:00,769
everyone to go to, I don't know, Moscone West to do something.

691
00:44:00,809 --> 00:44:01,329
That would have been...

692
00:44:02,169 --> 00:44:02,990
Super complicated.

693
00:44:05,351 --> 00:44:08,953
One of the important features in the boards is that it's 25

694
00:44:09,554 --> 00:44:13,056
squares, so the learning, it is super hard.

695
00:44:13,376 --> 00:44:16,518
So one thing we did was that we decided that one of the

696
00:44:16,578 --> 00:44:19,920
chests is easy chest, another chest is a medium chest, and

697
00:44:19,940 --> 00:44:21,341
the third one is the hard chest.

698
00:44:22,342 --> 00:44:25,483
And every mission that leads to the easy chest is actually

699
00:44:25,523 --> 00:44:26,144
super easy.

700
00:44:27,138 --> 00:44:29,259
So that when you're semi-randomly doing

701
00:44:29,359 --> 00:44:32,540
things on the map, you actually see that these quests are

702
00:44:32,560 --> 00:44:33,460
starting to complete.

703
00:44:33,560 --> 00:44:36,322
And then you're actually figuring out that there's an

704
00:44:36,402 --> 00:44:38,923
opportunity of grabbing the easy chest if you just

705
00:44:38,983 --> 00:44:40,203
coordinate the efforts a little bit.

706
00:44:40,663 --> 00:44:43,044
And then, of course, when you have done that, you've done

707
00:44:43,164 --> 00:44:45,245
quite a bit of work towards the medium chest as well.

708
00:44:45,625 --> 00:44:48,226
So that will be half complete when you're

709
00:44:48,246 --> 00:44:49,147
done with the easy chest.

710
00:44:49,967 --> 00:44:51,388
And the same goes on with the hard chest.

711
00:44:53,348 --> 00:44:57,571
One thing we also did here is that some of the missions are, as the previous example,

712
00:44:57,611 --> 00:45:02,334
they are lone wolf quests so that one player needs to focus their efforts on one task.

713
00:45:02,895 --> 00:45:05,376
This has been a really interesting, dramatic tool for us.

714
00:45:06,357 --> 00:45:11,080
One thing we can do, for instance, is that we take the best player away from some difficult

715
00:45:11,140 --> 00:45:15,103
mission so that the others need to shine because the best player is focusing on the lone wolf

716
00:45:15,143 --> 00:45:15,343
mission.

717
00:45:16,024 --> 00:45:20,432
The lone wolf missions also become competitions between players when both want their face on the

718
00:45:20,452 --> 00:45:25,842
wall and then they are effectively wasting their efforts in this glory hunt, which is really nice.

719
00:45:28,655 --> 00:45:33,377
We worked even further with trying to make sure that these guild wars would always be...

720
00:45:35,118 --> 00:45:38,539
So that the players would also have hope in completing the guild wars.

721
00:45:39,099 --> 00:45:41,700
So here you can see the difficulty curve of the guild wars.

722
00:45:42,181 --> 00:45:46,663
Basically on the left side you can see the tier 1 and on the right hand side you can see tier 20.

723
00:45:47,563 --> 00:45:50,484
And you can see the small numbers, but I can tell you

724
00:45:50,524 --> 00:45:54,727
that the highest, most difficult guild board has

725
00:45:55,147 --> 00:45:58,529
difficulty multiplier of about 300, compared to the

726
00:45:58,569 --> 00:46:01,630
difficulty multiplier of about one of the easiest board.

727
00:46:02,170 --> 00:46:05,132
So on the first board, you have to win 10 battles.

728
00:46:05,412 --> 00:46:09,194
On the last board, you will have to win 3,000 battles.

729
00:46:10,195 --> 00:46:12,035
So they get extremely difficult towards

730
00:46:12,075 --> 00:46:12,856
the end of the stack.

731
00:46:15,087 --> 00:46:17,569
It was hard for us because players were getting stuck on

732
00:46:17,609 --> 00:46:21,411
the boards, and then your social dynamics start to go

733
00:46:21,492 --> 00:46:24,193
awry, because when you lose hope, then there's nothing fun

734
00:46:24,233 --> 00:46:24,934
in the game anymore.

735
00:46:25,194 --> 00:46:27,536
And then some people stop playing, and then it gets even

736
00:46:27,596 --> 00:46:28,436
harder to progress.

737
00:46:28,937 --> 00:46:31,778
So one of the important things we did was that, as you can

738
00:46:31,838 --> 00:46:35,501
see here, the difficulty curve of the first board of every

739
00:46:35,541 --> 00:46:37,762
tier is actually quite lenient.

740
00:46:38,083 --> 00:46:40,885
So no matter where you are, you can always complete the

741
00:46:40,925 --> 00:46:41,425
first board.

742
00:46:42,185 --> 00:46:45,866
The second board, which is the medium board, is a little bit of a challenging,

743
00:46:46,286 --> 00:46:48,067
and then the real push is the third one.

744
00:46:48,987 --> 00:46:53,188
But then there's another aesthetic that is really nice here, besides the aesthetic of hope,

745
00:46:53,568 --> 00:46:57,109
which is that the first board is always a really nice reward for you.

746
00:46:57,550 --> 00:47:02,951
Like in Clash of Clans, the reward for upgrading your Town Hall level is not really the better Town Hall,

747
00:47:03,251 --> 00:47:06,992
the reward in Clash of Clans is that you get to upgrade all your stuff really fast,

748
00:47:07,072 --> 00:47:09,253
and so the game becomes very fun to play.

749
00:47:09,833 --> 00:47:11,896
And here the same thing happens with the first board

750
00:47:11,936 --> 00:47:14,100
being fun to play and super quick and super fast.

751
00:47:16,363 --> 00:47:19,408
We found this math of hope really important part of the

752
00:47:19,448 --> 00:47:20,770
dramatics of the Guild Board system.

753
00:47:22,993 --> 00:47:24,936
So let's look at the core loop.

754
00:47:25,760 --> 00:47:30,083
It was a little bit complicated already, but then there are different kinds of missions

755
00:47:30,103 --> 00:47:30,824
that you have to do.

756
00:47:31,224 --> 00:47:35,727
And you have to start optimizing not only between the rare missions and the safe house

757
00:47:35,747 --> 00:47:40,351
that you want to save, you have to also start to coordinate with your friends and you have

758
00:47:40,371 --> 00:47:44,734
to start to figure out which are the best ways for me to contribute in these guild

759
00:47:44,794 --> 00:47:45,035
quests.

760
00:47:45,996 --> 00:47:52,359
And it gets pretty complicated because there are now multiple social systems that are interacting in unpredictable ways.

761
00:47:52,740 --> 00:48:00,043
You have both the local social system of safe houses, and then you have the guild-based social system of the guild boards.

762
00:48:00,424 --> 00:48:08,548
And both of them are dynamic, both of them are unpredictable, both of them are gamed by not only you but also your guild.

763
00:48:08,868 --> 00:48:10,829
And that makes the game quite deep, actually.

764
00:48:12,163 --> 00:48:15,265
Of course, every game gets stale over time, so we also

765
00:48:15,345 --> 00:48:16,406
added some token events.

766
00:48:16,446 --> 00:48:19,108
So sometimes you want to go somewhere even to get this

767
00:48:19,208 --> 00:48:20,549
week's special mission tokens.

768
00:48:22,891 --> 00:48:27,574
I think I heard of the term smart depth first time about

769
00:48:27,634 --> 00:48:29,356
10 years ago in a WUGA presentation.

770
00:48:29,816 --> 00:48:33,459
And their point was that you want to enrich your core loop

771
00:48:33,539 --> 00:48:36,101
while you want to keep your core loop just as it is.

772
00:48:36,701 --> 00:48:38,482
So you want to add smart depth.

773
00:48:39,183 --> 00:48:40,244
while keeping it simple.

774
00:48:40,764 --> 00:48:44,087
And I think we succeed in our world in this task, because

775
00:48:44,107 --> 00:48:46,129
this is still a really simple decision space.

776
00:48:46,469 --> 00:48:47,830
You can't do anything wrong.

777
00:48:48,411 --> 00:48:49,472
You can just fail.

778
00:48:50,232 --> 00:48:52,914
You can just introduce waste in your process.

779
00:48:53,555 --> 00:48:54,736
There is no failure.

780
00:48:55,396 --> 00:48:56,257
Every time you log in.

781
00:48:57,198 --> 00:49:01,359
You pick a fight, you shoot something for 15 seconds, you progress in the game.

782
00:49:01,639 --> 00:49:04,740
But if you're really smart, you can progress a little bit more.

783
00:49:05,360 --> 00:49:08,941
And even for advanced players such as myself, sometimes I'm, I don't know,

784
00:49:08,981 --> 00:49:13,143
walking on the street and I don't want to think that much, while at other times I want to be

785
00:49:13,223 --> 00:49:17,464
super careful of my resource management. Like I have one energy, what is the best

786
00:49:17,524 --> 00:49:19,905
way for me to use this one energy here right now?

787
00:49:22,737 --> 00:49:26,462
Of course, from design perspective, this is kind of difficult to handle because there

788
00:49:26,482 --> 00:49:27,283
are so many options.

789
00:49:28,004 --> 00:49:30,687
So we were thinking, like, how can we simplify this?

790
00:49:31,388 --> 00:49:35,714
And then we figured out, like, let's just assume that players are scavenging quite optimally

791
00:49:35,774 --> 00:49:36,454
at all times.

792
00:49:36,895 --> 00:49:41,561
Let's just do all our Excel math, assuming that they get really good grades at all times.

793
00:49:42,542 --> 00:49:43,503
And that helped us a lot.

794
00:49:44,183 --> 00:49:46,565
And then we figured out, let's just assume that they put

795
00:49:46,625 --> 00:49:49,287
their stuff in really good safe houses at all times.

796
00:49:49,667 --> 00:49:51,949
And if they don't put their stuff in the really good safe

797
00:49:51,989 --> 00:49:54,051
houses at all times, then they're introducing waste, and

798
00:49:54,071 --> 00:49:54,911
that is their problem.

799
00:49:55,772 --> 00:49:58,114
And then we figured, let's assume they win all the

800
00:49:58,194 --> 00:49:59,394
battles, so we don't need to.

801
00:50:00,494 --> 00:50:02,696
Think about the difficulty in terms of economy design.

802
00:50:02,716 --> 00:50:04,178
Of course, we think about difficulty a lot.

803
00:50:04,518 --> 00:50:06,841
But in terms of economy design, you always win.

804
00:50:07,441 --> 00:50:09,524
And since location is just an opportunity,

805
00:50:09,904 --> 00:50:12,066
even the teleport flare feature is just like,

806
00:50:12,366 --> 00:50:14,349
we just assume that you have really good opportunities

807
00:50:14,409 --> 00:50:14,869
at all times.

808
00:50:15,650 --> 00:50:17,870
So from economy design perspective,

809
00:50:17,950 --> 00:50:19,291
this is how our game looks like.

810
00:50:19,891 --> 00:50:21,392
Time equals progress.

811
00:50:22,052 --> 00:50:24,573
And it's modulated by skill and effort

812
00:50:24,633 --> 00:50:27,614
so the player can introduce some waste if they are not ideal.

813
00:50:27,734 --> 00:50:28,894
And of course, no one is ideal.

814
00:50:29,534 --> 00:50:32,535
But at the same time, it's still the social fantasy

815
00:50:32,915 --> 00:50:36,817
of the walking dead surviving by pulling together and not apart.

816
00:50:41,398 --> 00:50:44,459
So time to start getting into actual takeaways.

817
00:50:45,570 --> 00:50:48,511
So looking at the core pillars that we set early on in the project,

818
00:50:48,551 --> 00:50:51,712
we wanted to achieve, we feel that we pretty much nailed all of these.

819
00:50:51,732 --> 00:50:53,893
You can play the game pretty much everywhere.

820
00:50:53,913 --> 00:50:56,494
It's always worth opening the game when you've moved.

821
00:50:57,614 --> 00:51:00,095
The game is quite couch play friendly,

822
00:51:00,915 --> 00:51:02,995
given the location-based aspect of it.

823
00:51:04,356 --> 00:51:07,397
Social mechanics, we wanted to make something that was really strong.

824
00:51:07,437 --> 00:51:08,197
We actually did it.

825
00:51:09,137 --> 00:51:11,138
And the game really does feel like The Walking Dead,

826
00:51:11,198 --> 00:51:13,298
where you absolutely have to coordinate your efforts

827
00:51:13,358 --> 00:51:15,219
with the other players in order to actually succeed.

828
00:51:15,990 --> 00:51:19,415
So even though the shape of the game that we ended up making was quite different

829
00:51:19,435 --> 00:51:22,100
from what we imagined at first, we're very happy with.

830
00:51:25,979 --> 00:51:28,400
A key takeaway is that when you do novel design,

831
00:51:28,680 --> 00:51:31,602
you have to do a lot of prototyping and validation.

832
00:51:31,982 --> 00:51:34,664
And the important thing in the prototyping and validation

833
00:51:34,764 --> 00:51:37,186
is that you have to accept that it takes time

834
00:51:37,606 --> 00:51:39,187
and it requires many failures.

835
00:51:39,607 --> 00:51:41,709
And of course, paper prototypes are the cheapest

836
00:51:41,789 --> 00:51:44,471
and quickest way to fail, which is very good.

837
00:51:44,891 --> 00:51:46,212
But ultimately, you will have to,

838
00:51:46,252 --> 00:51:47,573
especially with the social systems,

839
00:51:47,613 --> 00:51:50,094
you have to actually build good, proper prototypes.

840
00:51:50,314 --> 00:51:51,735
And we spent a lot of time doing that.

841
00:51:53,526 --> 00:51:59,009
So having said that, yes, you need to be able to and prepared to kill all the darlings, even if they're really cool.

842
00:52:00,070 --> 00:52:07,474
I personally like the, we as humans, very easily fall with the sunk cost fallacy,

843
00:52:07,574 --> 00:52:11,336
where we think that we put so much time and effort and love into a prototype,

844
00:52:11,456 --> 00:52:17,059
and it must succeed simply because we like it so much, or we invested so much energy into it.

845
00:52:17,579 --> 00:52:20,560
But let's all, as game designers and game developers,

846
00:52:20,600 --> 00:52:23,440
try to fight that and make sure that if something doesn't

847
00:52:23,521 --> 00:52:25,801
actually fit your game, just kill the feature away

848
00:52:25,961 --> 00:52:27,481
and your game's going to be so much better for it.

849
00:52:30,302 --> 00:52:32,623
Even though there are no references for novel design,

850
00:52:33,103 --> 00:52:34,503
you can always have references.

851
00:52:34,563 --> 00:52:36,804
And you should look outside the box for references

852
00:52:36,924 --> 00:52:37,624
if you don't have them.

853
00:52:38,824 --> 00:52:45,168
Our guild board system is basically a marriage of Disney Tsum Tsum's bingo boards combined

854
00:52:45,188 --> 00:52:51,231
with Everwing's guild quests and our shooting mechanics combine Operation Wolf with Whack-A-Mole.

855
00:52:51,852 --> 00:52:57,555
So the language of games is still very important when you don't have anything direct to look

856
00:52:57,575 --> 00:52:57,615
at.

857
00:53:00,707 --> 00:53:05,211
With the core loop, once you actually figure out something that really works,

858
00:53:05,792 --> 00:53:11,656
continue iterating and adding more features, but really do try to keep it simple and have the same

859
00:53:12,477 --> 00:53:17,681
way of people approaching how they play the game throughout the process. So you'll end up with a

860
00:53:17,701 --> 00:53:22,806
loop that is still easy to play, but has so much depth if the players actually really want to look

861
00:53:22,846 --> 00:53:23,046
for it.

862
00:53:25,123 --> 00:53:29,506
And finally, you need to iterate your own game until you're hooked to it.

863
00:53:30,287 --> 00:53:39,432
On the right hand side you can see a guild board on tier 3, which I completed alone because all my guildmates were slacking that week because I wanted to progress and they didn't.

864
00:53:42,334 --> 00:53:52,460
So, thank you, hope you enjoyed and really good to see so many people here despite the, I assume the party starting at 6 o'clock. So, I'm Sulka.

865
00:53:53,381 --> 00:53:54,061
My name is Markus.

866
00:53:55,059 --> 00:53:58,721
And please remember to fill up the feedback forms if you like the presentation.

867
00:53:58,741 --> 00:54:12,011
I assume we might have time for like maybe one question.

868
00:54:17,515 --> 00:54:24,340
I'm just curious about how long did you guys spend just in pre-production?

869
00:54:26,071 --> 00:54:32,519
So the core prototyping, I think we spent maybe 10 months on it.

870
00:54:32,619 --> 00:54:36,523
Actually doing things that ultimately mostly got chucked away.

871
00:54:37,605 --> 00:54:39,567
And the team was at some point...

872
00:54:40,658 --> 00:54:43,539
I remember the programmers asking,

873
00:54:43,780 --> 00:54:45,681
do we really want to spend all this time

874
00:54:45,781 --> 00:54:47,261
doing things that we're going to throw away?

875
00:54:47,341 --> 00:54:48,382
So we did, but we did.

876
00:54:48,402 --> 00:54:52,864
We did a huge refactoring pass of actually rewriting a lot of

877
00:54:52,884 --> 00:54:54,405
the code from the prototypes to be

878
00:54:54,445 --> 00:54:55,566
something that we could actually put

879
00:54:55,606 --> 00:54:56,666
into the final shipping product.

880
00:54:56,686 --> 00:54:58,667
Cool. Thank you.

881
00:55:04,971 --> 00:55:06,512
Cool. I guess that's it. Thank you.

882
00:55:10,706 --> 00:55:15,047
Thanks again. I never work on a location-based game, so maybe my question will be dumb, but

883
00:55:15,528 --> 00:55:22,771
did you see some changes in players' behavior based on climate, or like warm countries,

884
00:55:22,971 --> 00:55:27,133
or during the season? And did you make some adjustments with events or stuff like that,

885
00:55:27,193 --> 00:55:29,614
or rules based on level design to accommodate that?

886
00:55:33,038 --> 00:55:38,239
We are internally debating on how much those effects influence our game.

887
00:55:38,579 --> 00:55:41,100
Personally, I know that when my hands freeze, I stop playing.

888
00:55:41,960 --> 00:55:46,981
So in order to accommodate players like me, we have done some increase in the couch play

889
00:55:48,022 --> 00:55:53,143
lately to accommodate for the winter, but we don't really know conclusively.

890
00:55:54,720 --> 00:56:00,343
The other thing to keep in mind is the geography of the world is fundamentally different depending where you go.

891
00:56:00,483 --> 00:56:05,126
So one of the features of Helsinki is that the city blocks are huge.

892
00:56:06,086 --> 00:56:11,129
So the number of buildings that you actually see at any given point is actually not that big, because the buildings aren't so big.

893
00:56:11,830 --> 00:56:18,934
But if you open the game in India, like in typical Indian cities, the game has to load about 5,000 buildings, because they're all very small.

894
00:56:20,014 --> 00:56:22,615
So the way we've built, as humans have built,

895
00:56:23,575 --> 00:56:26,916
the systems in which we're living

896
00:56:26,936 --> 00:56:29,797
is so fundamentally different that if you

897
00:56:30,437 --> 00:56:33,398
want to design a game that actually works across the globe,

898
00:56:33,598 --> 00:56:36,779
it's not only how warm it is somewhere,

899
00:56:36,819 --> 00:56:39,320
but there's so many aspects that you actually need to look into

900
00:56:39,360 --> 00:56:41,701
and you need to play and teleport around the world,

901
00:56:42,461 --> 00:56:44,541
look at how the game works across the globe.

902
00:56:44,741 --> 00:56:48,242
So it's very complicated to actually isolate any one thing

903
00:56:48,262 --> 00:56:48,863
that would, um...

904
00:56:49,543 --> 00:56:52,733
make a difference to the players depending on where they are.

905
00:56:55,120 --> 00:56:55,401
Thank you.

